In[]:
import pandas as pd
import geopandas as gpd
import shapely

The green-belt area for Elmbridge is entity 610104 on the planning data service: https://www.planning.data.gov.uk/entity/610104

From this page it's possible to see the facts for the geometry field, which will show us if and how it has changed over time.

Facts come from resources, which are instances of data downloaded from an endpoint. Many of the datasets on the planning data service consist of data collected from multiple endpoints. In the case of the green-belt dataset this should be from endpoints for each annual release of data.

The facts page tells us the latest resource each fact came from. We can read this data into a table using the json link:

In[]:
facts_url = "https://www.planning.data.gov.uk/fact.json?dataset=green-belt&entity=610104&field=geometry"

elm_geom_fact_df = pd.read_json(facts_url, orient = "records")

# load wkt to geometry field
elm_geom_fact_df['value'] = elm_geom_fact_df['value'].apply(shapely.wkt.loads)
elm_geom_fact_gdf = gpd.GeoDataFrame(elm_geom_fact_df, geometry='value')
elm_geom_fact_gdf.set_crs(epsg=4326, inplace=True)
elm_geom_fact_gdf.to_crs(27700)

print(len(elm_geom_fact_gdf))
elm_geom_fact_gdf.head()

3

The entry dates for these facts reflect an update that was made on 2024-05-08 to add the two latest green-belt endpoints, meaning it's resource 2858fa51c91289f4ad90ee2e600aa7a586cac68884affc49efce4be06741b7e8 which would have been displayed before then.

The latest-entry-date means that this resource was last collected on 2022-10-07.

We can find the endpoint and source for this resource by using datasette to query the source and endpoint tables.

In[]:
query_url = "https://datasette.planning.data.gov.uk/digital-land.csv?sql=select%0D%0A+++re.resource%2C+%0D%0A+++re.endpoint%2C%0D%0A+++e.endpoint_url%2C+%0D%0A+++e.entry_date%2C%0D%0A+++s.documentation_url%0D%0Afrom+resource_endpoint+re%0D%0Ainner+join+endpoint+e+on+re.endpoint+%3D+e.endpoint%0D%0Ainner+join+source+s+on+e.endpoint+%3D+s.endpoint%0D%0Awhere+re.resource+IN+%28%0D%0A++%222858fa51c91289f4ad90ee2e600aa7a586cac68884affc49efce4be06741b7e8%22%2C%0D%0A++%22232a469fec0b0af41a628e1cc5203749af3c165156cb8ead3d6fefa52f751add%22%2C%0D%0A++%2254ff74f45e458c4e7d139689de57a8b7e7d768d9c1ccb11a0026903093842341%22%29&_size=max"

res_end_src_df = pd.read_csv(query_url)

# split out the year part of the endpoint url
res_end_src_df["release_year"] = res_end_src_df["endpoint_url"].str.split("&").apply(lambda x: x[3][-13:-6])

for i, r in res_end_src_df.iterrows():
    print(f"Resource: {r['resource']}")
    print(f"Resource collected from endpoint: {r['endpoint_url']}")
    print(f"Greenbelt endpoint release year: {r['release_year']}")
    print(f"Resource source documentation-url: {r['documentation_url']}")
    print("-" * 80)

This shows us that all of the resources which contributed facts for the geometry field of entity 610104 came from endpoints published on data.gov.uk.

The endpoint for the 2020-21 release of greenbelt data is no longer working, but the fact 9531bf14e911c1827215644a6d37bef67f73f7afc5c8286faf108ce1eb0e2e2d is a record of the information captured from the resource when the endpoint was last working. We can use this to see any differences between this and more recent data.

The map below compares the geometry facts from the 2020-21 and 2022-23 release endpoints.

  • Blue = area in both polygons
  • Red = area in 2020-21 but not in 2022-23
  • Green = area in 2022-23 but not in 2020-21
In[]:
# get geometry record for each year's release
gb_2020 = elm_geom_fact_gdf[elm_geom_fact_gdf["latest-resource"] == "2858fa51c91289f4ad90ee2e600aa7a586cac68884affc49efce4be06741b7e8"]
gb_2022 = elm_geom_fact_gdf[elm_geom_fact_gdf["latest-resource"] == "54ff74f45e458c4e7d139689de57a8b7e7d768d9c1ccb11a0026903093842341"]

# work out differences
both = gb_2022.overlay(gb_2020, how = "intersection")
lost = gb_2020.overlay(gb_2022, how = "difference")
gained = gb_2022.overlay(gb_2020, how = "difference")

# show on map
m1 = both.explore(
    color = "blue",
    tooltip = False,
    tiles = "CartoDB positron", 
    style_kwds = {"fillOpacity" : "0.3", "stroke" : False})

m2 = lost.explore(
    m = m1,
    color = "red",
    tooltip = False,
    style_kwds = {"fillOpacity" : "0.5", "stroke" : False})

gained.explore(
    m = m2,
    color = "green",
    tooltip = False,
    style_kwds = {"fillOpacity" : "0.5", "stroke" : False})

It's clear there are some substantial differences between the 2022-23 and 2020-21 Elmbridge green-belt data on the planning data service, with some roads appearing within or outside the greenbelt in either dataset.

We can compare the 2020-21 geometry from the planning data service with the source data on gov.uk to confirm whether this discrepancy comes from the source data or from processing behind the planning data service.

In[]:
import requests

# get 2020-21 data from Gov.uk source and restrict to Elmbridge
r = requests.get("https://maps.communities.gov.uk/geoserver/dclg_inspire/ows?service=WFS&version=1.0.0&request=GetFeature&typeName=dclg_inspire%3AEngland_Green_Belt_2020_21_WGS84&outputFormat=JSON")
gb_gov = gpd.GeoDataFrame.from_features(r.json(), crs=4326)
gb_gov.to_crs(27700)

gb_gov_elm = gb_gov[gb_gov["LAD_CD"] == "E07000207"]

The map below compares the 2020-21 green-belt data for Elmbridge from the planning data service and that published on data.gov.uk (which is the source).

There are no noticeable differences, apart from some tiny slivers at the edge which are likely minor discrepancies from crs transformations. This suggests the differences between 2020-21 and 2022-23 data orginate from the data.gov.uk source datasets.
